{
  "text": "Before giving more details, recall that Stefanov and Uhlmann [CITATION_1] have shown that under a microlocal condition on the geodesics, one can recover the singularities of functions from their X-ray transform, and indeed from a partial X-ray transform (where only some geodesics are included in the X-ray family M ). (In fact, they also showed analogous statements for the transforms on tensors.) Roughly speaking what one needs is that given a covector \u03bd = (z, \u03b6), one needs to have a geodesic in M normal to \u03b6 at z such that in a neighborhood of \u03bd a simplicity condition is satisfied. Indeed, under these assumptions, a microlocal version of the normal operator, (QI) * (QI), where Q microlocalizes to M roughly speaking, is an elliptic pseudodifferential operator. Now, in dimension \u2265 3, if the boundary \u2202X is convex, one can use geodesics which are almost tangent to \u2202X to give a family M which satisfies the above conditions for \u03bd with z near \u2202X. While this gives a recovery of singularities for the local problem we are considering, it yields no invertibility or reconstruction. Indeed for the latter we would like to have (QI) * (QI) to be an invertible operator on a space of functions on O c ; in particular, as one approaches x = \u2212c one would need to only allow integrals over geodesics in a narrow cone, becoming tangent tox = \u2212c, which takes one outside the framework of standard pseudodifferential operators.",
